agency. Writing for fans as well as scholars, Diana Adesola Mafe looks at representations of black womanhood and girlhood in American and British speculative film and television, including 28 Days Later, AVP: Alien vs. Predator, Children of Men, Beasts of the Southern Wild, Firefly, and Doctor Who: Series 3. Each of these has a subversive black female character in its main cast, and Mafe draws on critical race, postcolonial, and gender theories to explore each film and show, placing the black female characters at the center of the analysis and demonstrating their agency. The first full study of black female characters in speculative film and television, Where No Black Woman Has Gone Before shows why heroines such as Lex in AVP and Zoë in Firefly are inspiring a generation of fans, just as Uhura did.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBlacks on television. 0aFantasy filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aFantasy television programsxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror television programsxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryy21st century. 0aScience fiction filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aScience fiction television programsxHistory and criticism. 0aSex role in motion pictures. 0aSex role on television. 0aTelevision programsxHistoryy21st century. 0aWomen on television. 0aWomen, Black, in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film / Genres / Science Fiction & Fantasy.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31522440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477315248423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477315248/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK